# Rate Limiting Walkthrough — BatchHost-Pro

## Overview

This walkthrough covers implementing **multi-tier rate limiting** in the BatchHost-Pro Flask server to protect against brute-force login attacks, agent API abuse, and excessive dashboard polling — all without adding external dependencies like Redis.

---

## Threat Model

Before writing code, here's what we're protecting against:

| Threat | Target Endpoint(s) | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| Brute-force login | `/api/auth/login` | Account takeover |
| Credential stuffing | `/api/auth/login` | Mass account compromise |
| Agent registration spam | `/api/agent/register` | Fake agents, data pollution |
| Heartbeat flooding | `/api/agent/heartbeat` | Server overload, disk thrashing |
| API scraping | `/api/agents`, `/api/scripts`, etc. | Data exfiltration, DoS |
| Page flooding | `/dashboard`, `/agents`, etc. | Resource exhaustion |

---

## Strategy: Tiered Rate Limits

Different endpoints need different limits. A login attempt is far more sensitive than a dashboard page view.

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    RATE LIMIT TIERS                      │
├──────────────┬──────────────┬───────────────┬────────────┤
│   CRITICAL   │    AGENT     │   STANDARD    │  RELAXED   │
│  5 req/min   │ 60 req/min   │  30 req/min   │ 120/min    │
│              │              │               │            │
│ /api/auth/   │ /api/agent/  │ /api/scripts  │ /dashboard │
│   login      │  heartbeat   │ /api/agents   │ /agents    │
│              │  register    │ /api/alerts   │ /scripts   │
│              │  script-*    │ /api/users    │ /settings  │
└──────────────┴──────────────┴───────────────┴────────────┘
```

